"Lohmann G., Haak H., Jungclaus J.H.","Estimating trends of Atlantic meridional overturning circulation from long-term hydrographic data and model simulations",2008,"Ocean Dynamics","58","2",,"127","138",,,10.1007/s10236-008-0136-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-46649097785&partnerID=40&md5=6a5365cf6a10fb2fced625f9c0ec124c","Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bussestr. 24, Bremerhaven 27570, Germany; Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, Hamburg 20146, Germany","Lohmann, G., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bussestr. 24, Bremerhaven 27570, Germany; Haak, H., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Bussestr. 24, Bremerhaven 27570, Germany, Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, Hamburg 20146, Germany; Jungclaus, J.H., Max-Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstr. 53, Hamburg 20146, Germany","The ocean meridional overturning circulation (MOC) plays a central role for the climate in the Atlantic realm. Since scenarios for future climate change indicate a significant reduction of the MOC under global warming, an assessment of variations and trends of the real MOC is important. Using observations at ocean weather ship (OWS) stations and along oceanic sections, we examine the hydrographic information that can be used to determine MOC trends via its signature in water mass properties obtained from model simulations with the climate model ECHAM5/MPI-OM. We show that temperature trends at mid-latitudes provide useful indirect measure of large-scale changes of deep circulation: A mid-depth warming is related to MOC weakening and a cooling to MOC strengthening. Based on our model experiments, we argue that a continuation of measurements at key OWS sites may contribute to a timely detection of a possible future MOC slowdown and to separate the signal from interannual-to-multidecadal MOC variability. The simulations suggest that the subsurface hydrographic information related to MOC has a lower variability than the MOC trend measured directly. Based on our model and the available long-term hydrographic data, we estimate non-significant MOC trends for the last 80 years. For the twenty-first century, however, the model simulations predict a significant MOC decline and accompanied mid-depth warming trend.","Atlantic meridional circulation; Ocean circulation; Ocean weather ship stations; Temperature trends","Climate change; Global warming; Oceanography; (p ,p ,t) measurements; Atlantic; Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC); Century (CO); climate modelling; Future climate; Hydrographic data; Indirect measure; Meridional overturning circulation (MOC); Mid-latitudes; model experiments; model simulations; Ocean weather; Significant reduction; temperature trends; water mass properties; Mathematical models; estimation method; hydrography; meridional circulation; oceanic circulation; temperature; twenty first century; Atlantic Ocean",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., Marotzke, J., Nordhaus, W.D., Overpeck, J.T., Peteet, D.M., Pielke Jr., R.A., Pierrehumbert, R.T., Wallace, J.M., Abrupt climate change (2003) Science, 299, pp. 2005-2010. , doi:10.1126/science.1081056; Arbic, B.K., Owens, W.B., Climate warming of Atlantic intermediate waters (2001) J Climate, 14, pp. 4091-4108; Baehr, J., Hirschi, J., Beismann, J.O., Marotzke, J., Monitoring the meridional overturning circulation in the North Atlantic: A model-based array design study (2004) J Mar Res, 62, pp. 283-312. , 3; Baehr, J., Keller, K., Marotzke, J., Detecting potential changes in the meridional overturning circulation at 26° N in the Atlantic (2007) Clim Change, , http://www.dx.doi.org/10.1007/s10584-006-9153-z; Baehr, J., Haak, H., Alderson, S., Cunningham, S.A., Jungclaus, J.H., Marotzke, J., Timely detection of changes in the meridional overturning circulation at 26° N in the Atlantic (2007) J Clim, 20, pp. 5827-5841; Black, D.E., Peterson, L.C., Overpeck, J.T., Kaplan, A., Evans